rking on eastern europe and the former soviet union to examine in depth three waves of democratic change that took place in eleven different former communist nations its essays draw important conclusions about the rise development and breakdown of both democracy and dictatorship in each country and together provide a rich comparative perspective on the post communist world the first democratic wave to sweep this region encompasses the rapid rise of democratic regimes from 1989 to 1992 from the ashes of communism and communist states the second wave arose with accession to the european union from 2004 to 2007 and the third with the electoral defeat of dictators 1996 to 2005 in croatia serbia georgia and ukraine although these three waves took place in different countries and involved different strategies they nonetheless shared several overarching commonalities international factors played a role in all three waves as did citizens demanding political change further each wave revealed not just victorious democrats but also highly resourceful authoritarians the authors of each chapter in this volume examine both internal and external dimensions of both democratic success and failure parent research program on evaluating international influences on democratic development program topics democracy international influences croatia europe georgia russia serbia ukraine search cddrl search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages publication news new books released by cddrl faculty september 24 2009 cddrl fsi stanford news publications of interest the fourth wave of democracy and dictatorship noncooperative transitions in the postcommunist world michael a mcfaul world politics vol 54 2 2002 html+ cover democratization in postcommunist europe illiberal regimes and the leverage of international actors milada anna vachudova cddrl working papers 2006 pdf+ the origins of authoritarianism in pakistan sumit ganguly cddrl worki